TY  - JOUR
T1  - Note—Rankings from Round-Robin Tournaments
AU  - Stob, Michael
Y1  - 1985/09/01
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.31.9.1191
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.31.9.1191
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1191
EP  - 1195
VL  - 31
IS  - 9
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - In a December 1983 article in Management Science, Stephen Goddard studies the problem of ranking contestants in a round-robin tournament. He gives objections to the usual method of ranking contestants by number of victories and proposes both an alternative method for ranking contestants and a criterion for determining the ?fairest? ranking. We argue here that his criterion is faulty and, in fact, falls prey to his own objections. We also show that his method, in any event, produces rankings which don't satisfy the criterion. Finally we describe a general class of models of competition which have been proposed to solve this problem and which lead to the usual method of ranking by number of victories.
AB  - In a December 1983 article in Management Science, Stephen Goddard studies the problem of ranking contestants in a round-robin tournament. He gives objections to the usual method of ranking contestants by number of victories and proposes both an alternative method for ranking contestants and a criterion for determining the ?fairest? ranking. We argue here that his criterion is faulty and, in fact, falls prey to his own objections. We also show that his method, in any event, produces rankings which don't satisfy the criterion. Finally we describe a general class of models of competition which have been proposed to solve this problem and which lead to the usual method of ranking by number of victories.
